<h2>Testing the non-accessible example</h2>

<h3>Keyboard navigation</h3>
For the stepbar we decided that the items shouldn't be clickable. So there is nothing to do.

<h3>Screen reader navigation</h3>
<p>At this stage, the vocalization of the stepbar is unsatisfactory.</p>
<p>If you listen to the component using a screen reader, a list of 5 items is read. Each item is properly vocalized; however, we have no indication of the current step.</p>

<h2>Vocalization support</h2>
<p>To improve the vocalization of this component it is necessary to think about the information that seems relevant to the user.</p>
<p>Visually, when we see this stepbar we have access to the following information:</p>
<ul>
      <li><b>The name of the current step,</b></li>
      <li><b>the number of total steps,</b></li>
      <li><b>the number of remaining steps,</b></li>
      <li>the name of each step.</li>
</ul>

<p>Ideally we should have the same level of information with as without a screen reader. That being said, it can be tedious to have too much information to listen to. Therefore, we will focus on the bold information listed above (the three first items in our list).</p>

<p><b>Possible example of vocalization:</b> “Delivery options, step 3 of 5.”</p>

<p>Technically, there are several ways to achieve this. We could try to hide inactive items from the screen reader and modify the vocalization of the selected item. However, given that this component changes according to the width of the screen (responsive design), the easiest way is to completely hide this component from the screen reader with the <code>aria-hidden="true"</code> attribute. Finally, add an <a href="../accessible-hiding/">accessible hiding</a> <code>span</code> containing the text to vocalize.</p>

<p>Accessible hiding allows to hide a text, but ensures that it is correctly vocalized by the screen reader. It is done through a simple <abbr>CSS</abbr> class. In the <a href="http://boosted.orange.com/css/#helper-classes-screen-readers">Boosted</a> and <a href="http://getbootstrap.com/css/#helper-classes-screen-readers">Bootstrap</a> libraries there is an accessible hiding class named <code>visually-hidden</code>.</p>
<p>See <a href="../accessible-hiding/">the accessible hiding example</a> for more information.</p>

<h2>Accessible example</h2>

<span class="visually-hidden">Delivery options, step 3 of 5</span>
<div class="row">
<ul class="o-wizard-step-bar" data-steps="5" aria-hidden="true">
    <li class="visited">
      <div class="arrow" aria-hidden="true"></div>
      <div>1 <span class="hidden-xs hidden-sm">Identification</span></div>
    </li>
    <li class="visited">
        <div class="arrow" aria-hidden="true"></div>
